Brief Introduction

In the last part, we run the homeless dataset in the Logistic Regression. The Logistic Regression could show the statistical relationship between the Independent Variables and the Dependent Variables, but it cannot display the statistc significant level for each single factors. To get more detailed regression model, I applied the Homeless dataset in the Poisson Regression Model.Poisson regression is a generalized linear model form of regression analysis, and it sometimes being called as log-linear model, using the log as an important function inside regression model. ####Installing the Package

Poisson Regression Model

Lets subset out some variables that we want to use

Now we want to estimate a poission regression. Because the independent variable of our data is not linear (the homeless shelter is skewed), we will regress it with a poisson regression.

From the regression summary table we can see that there are total of eleven dependent variables reaching the significant level (<= 0.05), which means they are significant factors in this model, having certain spatial relationship with the location of shelters in Philadelphia (either positive or negative). How do we interpret those coefficients? With the below example, we can say that conditional on the variables in thee model, for every 1000 meter farther from an homeless shelter, the expected number of alchoel store will fall by 0.58%.

(1 - exp(5.761e-06)) * 1000 
## [1] -0.005761017

Plotting the Predicted homeless shelters.

Through evaulating the 11 factors coefficiency value, we can predict the location of homeless shelter in Philadelphia. The darker color of the pixel represents the higher probability that this pixel would have a homeless shelter on top. ####Write Data into csv file From the next step, the exported csv file will be moved to ArcMap to be better processed.The exported csv contains the same dataset values except it has one extra column called fitted values, which is being generated from previous steps. *The appendix 1 of this file contains the processing steps inside ArcMap.

Goodness of Fit

Read the processed GIS data layer into R

Via reading the processed data into the R, we now is able to

##   FID_1 gridcode Count_   Category  kernelPct  fittedPct
## 1     0        4      2 90% - 100% 0.21052632 0.09523810
## 2     1        1      5  70% - 89% 0.05263158 0.23809524
## 3     2        2      4  50% - 69% 0.10526316 0.19047619
## 4     3        3      0 90% - 100% 0.15789474 0.00000000
## 5     4        4      1  70% - 89% 0.21052632 0.04761905
## 6     5        5      9  50% - 69% 0.26315789 0.42857143

The most ideal group is the 70-89%, due to its relatively high predicted risk levels, but our homeless shelters hotsport has heavy weight between range 50% - 69%, which is an OK range, but not as precise as the other two levels. One possible reason behind may be the number of dependent factors in the dataset is only 11, and the sample size is relatively small (approximately 30,000 records), so that they slightly influenced the level of preciseness of the model. Because our model reaches a fairly good level of Goodnedss of Fit, it can be generalized to other places (if the predicting place have more similar features like Philly, the model will generate a result with higher precise level. )
